# Economy of Bahrain

The [Manama](/Manama) skyline, a testament to what ambition can build when fueled by both finite resources and the enduring human desire for commerce.

The economic landscape of [Bahrain](/Bahrain), a small island nation nestled in the [Persian Gulf](/Persian_Gulf), has undergone a deliberate and often arduous transformation in recent decades. While the allure of [oil and gas](/Petroleum_industry_in_Bahrain) remains a significant, if diminishing, factor, the kingdom has consciously steered its economic vessel away from singular reliance on these volatile commodities. As of 2024, the extraction of hydrocarbons still occupies a notable position, ranking as the third-largest sector within the national economy, a lingering reminder of its foundational wealth. Bahrain, ever pragmatic, has explicitly endorsed a [mixed economy system](/Mixed_economy), a blend of market forces and strategic governmental oversight, a predictable choice for a region balancing traditional structures with modern imperatives.

Since the latter part of the 20th century, the island has channeled substantial investment into developing its [banking](/Banking) and [tourism](/Tourism) sectors, a calculated pivot towards more sustainable, service-oriented industries. This foresight was seemingly validated in 2008 when Bahrain was lauded as the world's fastest-growing financial center by the City of London's [Global Financial Centres Index](/Global_Financial_Centres_Index). The burgeoning banking and financial services sector, particularly its robust embrace of [Islamic banking](/Islamic_banking) principles, has undeniably reaped benefits from the broader regional prosperity, largely instigated by the persistent global appetite for oil.

Despite these diversification efforts, [petroleum](/Petroleum) continues to cast a long shadow over Bahrain's fiscal realities. It remains the nation's foremost exported product, singularly responsible for a staggering 60% of all export receipts, a formidable 70% of [government revenues](/Government_revenue), and still contributing a not-insignificant 11% to the overall [Gross Domestic Product](/Gross_domestic_product). Following petroleum, [aluminum](/Aluminium_Bahrain) products claim the mantle as the second most significant export, a testament to energy-intensive industrial development, trailed by the more ethereal categories of financial services and construction materials.

In the 2020 edition of the [Index of Economic Freedom](/Index_of_Economic_Freedom), Bahrain positioned itself as having the fourth-freest economy across the [Middle East](/Middle_East) and [North Africa](/North_Africa) region, securing the 40th position globally. However, an alternative assessment presents a more modest ranking, placing Bahrain at 70th, suggesting that economic liberty, like beauty, can often be in the eye of the beholder. Regardless of specific numerical placement, the [World Bank](/World_Bank) has recognized Bahrain as a [high-income economy](/High_income_economy), a designation that, while not guaranteeing perpetual prosperity, certainly implies a certain baseline of affluence.

